observations.recommendation:
In order to ensure optimal appropriation and utilization of the LDRRMF, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the MDRRMO and LDRRMC to:

Monitor regularly the utilization of the fund, evaluate the reasons for its non-implementation, and ascertain the present viability of the PPAs; otherwise, re-align or re-program the funds towards more important initiatives;



Prioritize the implementation of PPAs under Continuing Appropriations. In the event of discontinuance, the PPAs may be re-programmed for more relevant projects; 



Judiciously plan the use of the unexpended balances of the LDRRMF from previous years, which were transferred to the special trust fund (STF), by including under a separate section in the LDRRMFIP the list of priority projects and activities to be charged out of the said funds; and



Refrain from charging administrative costs from the fund.

We recommended that the Management: 

Refrain from payment of expenditures through reimbursements;


Cease payment of expenditures to other official or employee unless he is a disbursing officer;


Pay directly to suppliers who delivered goods in accordance with RA No. 9184;



Refund the amount of ₱25,000.00 given to SK Federation and West Tricycle Operators and Drivers Association for financial assistance which are private purpose in nature; and

Adhere to laws, rules and regulations pertaining to financial transactions of the government to ensure sound internal control which will ultimately result to fair presentation of financial statements, and efficient and effective use of government funds.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
MA to;
Prepare and maintain SPLC to monitor Semi-Expendables maintained by the Municipality; and
Update applicable reports and registries in compliance with Section 4.7 of COA Circular No. 2022-006.
GSO to;
Reconcile with the Accounting Office and prepare ICS for all serviceable semi-expendables issued in prior years;
Prepare and maintain SPC and RegSPI to adequately monitor acquired and issued semi-expendables; and
Prepare and furnish copies of the RegSPI and RPCSP, to the MA, to serve as basis for the proper recording and reporting of semi-expendable items in the FS.

We therefore recommended that the LCE direct the GAD Focal Point System to:
Enhance the use of gender analysis tools in identifying gender issues by ensuring that staff are adequately trained on their application, including the HGDG and other relevant assessment tools;
Maximize the use of the GAD Database by incorporating sex-disaggregated data during the planning and design of GAD PPAs, and by using it regularly to validate proposed programs and interventions;
Ensure that all proposed GAD activities are clearly linked to identified gender issues through proper documentation, analysis, and alignment with identified GAD objectives; and
Strengthen internal review procedures to prevent the inclusion of general welfare programs in the GAD Fund unless these are supported by data showing specific gender-related concerns.

We recommended that the LCE direct the MA and AO/Human Resource Management Officer to:
Immediately compute the correct taxes due on the taxable portion of the SRI disbursed in CY 2024, withhold the corresponding taxes from the affected municipal personnel, and remit these taxes promptly to the BIR. Furthermore, conduct a thorough review and revision of the overall compensation tax computations to ensure the proper classification and tax treatment of all compensation and benefits;
Develop and implement a strategic, perpetual system for the computation of taxes on compensation by establishing a centralized database that enables real-time monitoring and adjustments. This system should facilitate continuous tracking of compensation and benefits, allowing for accurate and timely tax withholding throughout the year, especially during year-end reconciliations;
Allocate a budget for training expenses to enable personnel assigned to tax matters to attend seminars/trainings conducted by the BIR, aimed at enhancing their understanding of the correct tax treatment of compensation and employee benefits and;
Formally turn over the payroll preparation to the HRMO, and ensure close coordination with the personnel responsible for tax withholding to guarantee that the correct taxes are properly deducted from the payroll.

We recommended that the LCE direct the AAO/HRMO and MA to:
Coordinate with other responsible offices to ensure immediate updating and regular reconciliation of employee records with the GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth, to prevent discrepancies and ensure accurate remittances and benefit eligibility;
Maintain a SL, database, or any equivalent system to accurately monitor and regularly update the monthly contributions and remittances of each employee;
For over-the-counter payments, establish a policy requiring the periodic reporting of payments and the submission of proofs of payment to the HR/Accounting Office;
Conduct a regular review of the monthly premiums deducted from payroll/disbursement vouchers for remittance to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth, and ensure that amounts withheld are consistent with the amounts required to be remitted monthly; and
Strictly abide with the provisions of Section 5(c) of RA 8291, Sections 6(a) and 3(e) of Rule VII of IRR of RA No. 9769, and Section 19(d) of Title III Rule III of the Revised IRR of RA 7875, to avoid administrative sanctions.

