We recommended for the following corrective measures:

the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer exert more effort to reconcile the difference of P115,965,910.45 existing between the accounting records of PPE and RPCPPE;
the Inventory Committee conduct physical inventory of assets taken up in the Special Education Fund books with acquisition cost of P1,109,957.57to determine its actual existence and condition and prepare the Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
the General Services Office provide details of the property totaling P211,830,213.37 taken up in the RPCPPE in lump sum as beginning balances;
the General Services Officer submit documents relating to the donated and disposed motor vehicles to the Accounting Office for recording/dropping from the books;
the Municipal Accountant prepare Ledger Card for each category of Property Plant and Equipment; and
the General Services Officer maintain Property Card (PC) for property, plant and equipment acquired by the Municipality for proper monitoring and control.

We recommended that the General Services Office ensure adequate control over the motor vehicles of the Municipality by performing the following control measures:

Immediately cause the registration in the name of the Municipality the motor vehicles still registered in the name of the previous owners and follow-up with the Land Transportation Office the car plates of motor vehicles with private plates and those with no plate numbers yet;
Prepare the required Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all motor vehicles found unserviceable and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor to facilitate the disposal of the same;
Undertake proper disposal of the unserviceable vehicles in accordance with the procedures in COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992;
Ensure proper maintenance of transportation equipment for the safety of the users and to reach the maximum useful life of the asset; and
See to it that motor vehicles are covered with insurance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

the implemention of  the mandatory Segregation of Solid Waste at source and promote awareness of the constituents through information campaign in every barangay;
the implementation of the No Segregation, No Collection Policy;
the establishment of functional Material Recovery Facility in every barangay or cluster of barangays; and
strictly implement the No-Littering Ordinace and the Ban on the Use of Non-Biodegradable Plastic Bags in the Municipality.

In view of the foregoing, we recommend that management :
Give priority to the development projects and programs that partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures.
Utilize the fund in conformity with the guidelines set forth by the DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1;
Copies of approved contracts and purchase orders of infrastructure projects and procured goods and services should be submitted within five (5) days from their execution/issuance;
Paid vouchers should be supported with the necessary documentary requirements to ensure the legality and propriety of the transactions.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Budget Officer, Accountant and Treasurer to:

1.	exercise utmost diligence in the disposition of government funds;
2.	limit expenses to actual income received;
3.	make sure that obligations incurred are always supported by funds available for such purpose/s;
4.	ensure that inter-agency payables and other current liabilities that are considered as trust receipts should be utilized only for the specific purpose for which these were created or received; and
5.	remit to the concerned government agencies the funds collected by the Municipality in their behalf within the reglementary period to avoid the occurrence of cash deficit.
